{"from":"c5-internal","finding":"Found Consensus Engine multi-agent debate framework (EE Science Hackathon 2025) - uses persona engine + debate orchestrator + consensus engine with structured protocols. Also found AGI-DS Quality Auditing Assistant using multi-agent debate with affirmative/negative agents + confidence scores. Key blog: Plumbing Not People argues single-agent with skills outperforms multi-agent systems."}
{"from":"c4-docs","finding":"AWS Prescriptive Guidance multi-agent pattern: use SQS/EventBridge for agent communication, DynamoDB/S3 for shared memory (blackboard), Step Functions for orchestration with timeout/retry. Supervisor-collaborator hierarchy matches debate judge pattern."}
{"from":"c2-kb","finding":"CRITICAL: iMAD paper (arxiv 2511.11306) shows MAD uses 3-5x more tokens than single-agent with only 1.5-5.3% accuracy gain. Selective triggering via self-critique + classifier reduces tokens 92% while improving accuracy 13.5%. Key: dont debate everything, use convergence detection."}
{"from":"c1-internet","finding":"Critical finding: arxiv 2605.00914 shows isolated self-correction OUTPERFORMS unguided homogeneous multi-agent debate. Models frequently shift from correct to incorrect answers in response to peer reasoning (arxiv 2509.05396). Debate should be selective, not universal."}
{"from":"c2-kb","finding":"D3/SAMRE paper: 4-round debate with early stopping (if judge agrees 2 consecutive rounds) + jury achieves 5-8% accuracy gain over baseline. Multi-advocate parallel (MORE) is faster than iterative single-advocate. Key: stop when judge scores agree in same direction for 2 rounds."}
{"from":"c1-internet","finding":"CRITICAL: Problem Drift paper (EACL 2026) analyzed 170 debates - found lack of progress (35%), low-quality feedback (26%), lack of clarity (25%) as main causes. Agent drift paper shows progressive degradation over extended interactions. 7 rounds is likely TOO MANY - causes quality degradation."}
{"from":"c2-kb","finding":"Adaptive Stability Detection (NeurIPS 2025): Use KS-statistic on Beta-Binomial mixture to detect when debate has converged. Threshold 0.05 for 2 consecutive rounds. Reduces 10 rounds to 4-6 with <1% accuracy loss. Ensemble size 7 is optimal."}
{"from":"c4-docs","finding":"CRITICAL: Claude 3.7+ has 5x burndown rate for output tokens on Bedrock quotas. With 2000+ word responses (current system), each debate turn burns ~5000 output tokens × 5 = 25000 from TPM quota. Reducing max_tokens and enforcing concise responses is essential for concurrency."}
{"from":"c4-docs","finding":"Bedrock Structured Outputs: enforce JSON schema on responses via outputConfig.textFormat. Grammar cached 24h. Use to force debate agents to return structured {argument, signals, confidence} instead of free-form text - eliminates parsing failures and reduces token waste."}
{"from":"c3-context","finding":"iMAD paper (AAAI 2026) shows selective debate triggering reduces tokens by 92% while improving accuracy 13.5%. Key insight: MAD only helps on ~10-19% of cases. Confidence scores alone are unreliable for deciding when to debate. Need interpretable features + classifier."}
